{{Infobox scientist |name = Eckhard Meinrenken |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |residence = [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada |citizenship = German |nationality = |ethnicity = |fields = [[Mathematics]] |workplaces = [[University of Toronto]] |alma_mater = [[Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg]] im Breisgau |doctoral_advisor = [[Hartmann Roemer]] |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada]] |religion = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }} '''Eckhard Meinrenken''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|FRSC}} is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[mathematician]] specializing in [[Symplectic Geometry]], [[Lie theory|Lie Theory]], [[Mathematical Physics]]. He is a professor at the [[University of Toronto Department of Mathematics]].
He was an invited speaker at [[International Congress of Mathematicians]], Beijing—2002.<ref>[http://www.mathunion.org/db/ICM/Speakers/SortedByLastname.php ICM Plenary and Invited Speakers since 1897]</ref><ref>[http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM2002.2/Main/icm2002.2.0637.0642.ocr.pdf ''Clifford Algebras and the Duflo Isomorphism'']</ref>
